00:00:01,773 --> 00:00:02,434
Chapter 105 - The Blacksmith.

3
00:00:02,975 --> 00:00:28,688
Availing himself of the mild, summer-cool weather that now reigned in these latitudes, and in preparation for the peculiarly active pursuits shortly to be anticipated, Perth, the begrimed, blistered old blacksmith, had not removed his portable forge to the hold again, after concluding his contributory work for Ahab's leg, but still retained it on deck, fast-lashed to ring bolts by the foremast, being now almost incessantly invoked by the headsman.

4
00:00:28,668 --> 00:00:36,340
and harpeniers and bowsmen to do some little job for them, altering or repairing or new-shaping their various weapons and boat furniture.

5
00:00:37,161 --> 00:00:48,900
Often he would be surrounded by an eager circle, all waiting to be served, holding boat spades, pikeheads, harpoons, and lances, and jealously watching his every sooty movement as he toiled.

6
00:00:49,821 --> 00:00:54,709
Nevertheless, this old man's was a patient hammer wielded by a patient arm.

7
00:00:54,757 --> 00:00:58,384
No murmur, no impatience, no petulance did come from him.

8
00:00:59,306 --> 00:01:11,871
Silent, slow, and solemn, bowing over still further his chronically broken back, he toiled away, as if toil were life itself, and the heavy beating of his hammer, the heavy beating of his heart.

9
00:01:12,673 --> 00:01:13,795
And so it was.

10
00:01:14,534 --> 00:01:15,578
Most miserable!

11
00:01:15,598 --> 00:01:26,198
A peculiar walk in this old man, a certain slight but painful appearing yawing in his gait, had at an early period of the voyage excited the curiosity of the mariners.

12
00:01:26,583 --> 00:01:30,509
and to the importunity of their persisted questionings he had finally given in.

13
00:01:30,569 --> 00:01:35,856
And so it came to pass that everyone now knew the shameful story of his wretched fate.

14
00:01:36,477 --> 00:01:50,177
Belated, and not innocently, one bitter winter's midnight on the road running between two country towns, the blacksmith half-stupidly felt the deadly numbness stealing over him, and sought refuge in a leaning, dilapidated barn.

15
00:01:50,157 --> 00:01:53,325
The issue was the loss of the extremities of both feet.

16
00:01:54,006 --> 00:02:05,213
Out of this revelation part by part, at last came out the four acts of the gladness and the one long and as yet uncatastrophed fifth act of the grief of his life's drama.

17
00:02:05,648 --> 00:02:13,317
He was an old man who, at the age of nearly sixty, had postponedly encountered that thing in sorrows technicals called ruin.

18
00:02:13,337 --> 00:02:28,534
He had been an artisan of famed excellence, and with plenty to do, owned a house and garden, embraced a youthful, daughter-like, loving wife, and three blithe, ruddy children, every Sunday went to a cheerful-looking church, planted in a grove.

19
00:02:28,514 --> 00:02:38,317
But one night, under cover of darkness and further concealed in a most cunning disguisement, a desperate burglar slid into his happy home and robbed them all of everything.

20
00:02:38,898 --> 00:02:45,173
And darker yet to tell, the blacksmith himself did ignorantly conduct this burglar into his family's heart.

21
00:02:45,372 --> 00:02:46,796
It was the Bottle Conjurer.

22
00:02:46,856 --> 00:02:52,008
Upon the opening of that fatal cork, forth flew the fiend and shriveled up his home.

23
00:02:52,790 --> 00:02:59,567
Now, for prudent, most wise, and economic reasons, the blacksmith's shop was in the basement of his dwelling.

24
00:02:59,783 --> 00:03:18,503
but with a separate entrance to it, so that always had the young and loving healthy wife listened with no unhappy nervousness, but with vigorous pleasure, to the stout ringing of her young-armed old husband's hammer, whose reverberations, muffled by passing through the floors and walls, came up to her, not unsweetly, in her nursery.

25
00:03:18,543 --> 00:03:24,930
And so, to stout labor's iron lullaby, the blacksmith's infants were rocked to slumber.

26
00:03:25,045 --> 00:03:26,046
O woe on woe!

27
00:03:26,627 --> 00:03:29,792
O death, why canst thou not sometimes be timely?

28
00:03:30,473 --> 00:03:35,000
Hadst thou taken this old blacksmith to thyself ere his full ruin came upon him?

29
00:03:35,060 --> 00:03:46,497
Then had the young widow had a delicious grief, and her orphans a truly venerable legendary sire to dream of in their after years, and all of them a care-killing competency.

30
00:03:46,477 --> 00:04:01,302
But death plucked down some virtuous elder brother, on whose whistling daily toil solely hung the responsibilities of some other family, and left the worse-than-useless old man standing till the hideous rot of life should make him easier to harvest.

31
00:04:02,223 --> 00:04:03,085
Why tell the whole?

32
00:04:03,125 --> 00:04:12,180
The blows of the basement hammer every day grew more and more between, and each blow every day grew fainter than the last.

33
00:04:12,160 --> 00:04:19,147
The wife sat frozen at the window with tearless eyes, glitteringly gazing into the weeping faces of her children.

34
00:04:19,808 --> 00:04:20,769
The bellows fell.

35
00:04:21,450 --> 00:04:23,312
The forge choked up with cinders.

36
00:04:23,732 --> 00:04:24,733
The house was sold.

37
00:04:25,434 --> 00:04:28,397
The mother dived down into the long churchyard grass.

38
00:04:29,098 --> 00:04:30,960
Her children twice followed her thither.

39
00:04:31,761 --> 00:04:42,032
And the houseless, familyless old man staggered off a vagabond in crepe, his every woe unreverenced, his gray head a scorn to flaxen curls.

40
00:04:42,012 --> 00:04:49,324
Death seems the only desirable sequel for a career like this, but Death is only a launching into the region of the strange untried.

41
00:04:50,045 --> 00:04:57,777
It is but the first salutation to the possibilities of the immense, remote, the wild, the watery, the unshored.

42
00:04:57,757 --> 00:05:18,398
Therefore to the death-longing eyes of such men who still have left in them some interior compunctions against suicide, does the all-contributed and all-receptive ocean alluringly spread forth his whole plane of unimaginable, taking terrors and wonderful, new-life adventures, and from the hearts of infinite Pacifics the thousand mermaids sing to them,

43
00:05:18,378 --> 00:05:22,223
Come hither, broken-hearted, here is another life without the guilt of death.

44
00:05:22,243 --> 00:05:29,933
Come hither, bury thyself in a life which, to your now equally abhorred and abhorring, landed world, is more oblivious than death.

45
00:05:30,494 --> 00:05:32,637
Come hither, put up T.H.Y.

46
